🚀 1. Major CubeSat / Small Satellite Subsystems

A satellite is typically divided into functional subsystems, each responsible for a critical aspect of operation. Your OBC will interface with all of these.

🧠 1. OBC (On-Board Computer)
The “brain” of the satellite
Runs flight software (FSW)
Handles:
Task scheduling
Command execution
Data handling
Fault detection & recovery (FDIR)

👉 For your project: focus on RTOS design, watchdogs, redundancy, and communication buses (I2C, SPI, CAN, UART).

🔋 2. EPS (Electrical Power System)
Generates, stores, and distributes power
Components:
Solar panels
Battery pack
Power conditioning & regulation
Responsibilities:
Voltage regulation
Power budgeting
Load switching

👉 Firmware angle:

Battery monitoring
Power modes (safe mode, low-power mode)
Telemetry reporting
🧭 3. ADCS (Attitude Determination and Control System)
Controls satellite orientation (where it's pointing)
Sensors:
Sun sensors
Magnetometers
Gyroscopes
Actuators:
Reaction wheels
Magnetorquers

👉 Firmware angle:

Sensor fusion (e.g., Kalman filters)
Control loops (PID, state-space)
Real-time constraints
📡 4. TT&C (Telemetry, Tracking & Command)
Communication with ground station
Handles:
Uplink (commands)
Downlink (telemetry/data)

Components:

Transceiver
Antennas
Modem/protocol stack

👉 Firmware angle:

Packet protocols (AX.25 commonly used in CubeSats)
Error detection/correction
Command parsing
💾 5. CDH (Command & Data Handling)
Sometimes merged with OBC
Manages:
Data storage
File systems
Data routing between subsystems

👉 Firmware angle:

Flash memory management
Logging systems
Fault-tolerant storage
🌡️ 6. Thermal Control System (TCS)
Keeps components within safe temperatures
Passive:
Coatings, insulation
Active:
Heaters, sensors

👉 Firmware angle:

Temperature monitoring
Heater control logic
🧪 7. Payload
The mission-specific part (camera, sensor, experiment)
Can vary widely:
Imaging
RF experiments
Scientific sensors

👉 Firmware angle:

Device drivers
Data acquisition pipelines
Scheduling (when to run payload)
🧱 8. Structure & Mechanisms
Physical body of the satellite
Includes:
Frame
Deployment systems (antennas, solar panels)

👉 Firmware angle:

Deployment sequencing (burn wires, timers)
Safety interlocks
🛰️ 9. Propulsion (optional in CubeSats)
Used for orbit adjustments
Includes:
Thrusters
Tanks

👉 Firmware angle:

Safety-critical control
Timing and sequencing
🔗 How These Connect (Important for OBC Design)

Your OBC acts like a central hub:

         +--------+
         |  OBC   |
         +--------+
         /   |   \
      EPS   ADCS  TT&C
       |      |     |
    Sensors Actuators Radio

Common communication buses:

I2C → sensors
SPI → high-speed devices
UART → radios
CAN → robust subsystem comms (in advanced designs)
🧩 Key Embedded System Concepts You Should Know

For a realistic CubeSat firmware:

RTOS (e.g., FreeRTOS)
Fault tolerance (watchdogs, redundancy)
State machines (SAFE, NOMINAL, DETUMBLE modes)
Telemetry + telecommand protocols
Power-aware scheduling
Radiation effects (bit flips → error correction)
